Properties of TmPt(1 1 1) surface alloys Abstract Formation of surface alloys by annealing of thin Tm layers which were deposited on Pt(1 1 1) are investigated by photoemission and low energy electron diffraction (LEED). In addition, adsorption of CO was studied by temperature programmed desorption (TPD). For deposition of more than a monolayer of Tm, a (2 × 2) LEED pattern forms upon heating the sample to 600 C. The appearance of the (2 × 2) pattern is assigned to alloy formation (thick alloy). The Tm 5p and 4f core levels show shifts of 0.8 eV to lower binding energies upon alloying, while the major Tm 4d multiplet shows a 1.1 eV shift to lower binding energy. These Tm shifts are interpreted to be caused by different coordination in the alloys. The present experiments indicate that the surface of the alloy is Pt enriched. For Tm coverages of less than about one monolayer a modified (1 × 1) LEED pattern is observed (thin alloy). The core level shifts as observed for the thick alloy is not seen for the thin alloy. Finally, the work function of a thick evaporated Tm film was measured to be 3.3 eV.
1. Introduction
Rare earths (RE) and their intermetallic compounds exhibit a variety of interesting physical phenomena, e.g. strongly correlated electron effects, magnetism, and superconductivity. Other properties of the rare earth series include low workfunction and low surface free energy. The latter property suggests that RE may be suited for formation of surface alloys, since the RE may have a tendency to be located near the surface and not be dissolved in the bulk. One particular topic of interest is the modification of surface reactivity by alloy formation, which is of relevance for corrosion as well as catalytic properties.
Here we report on a study of thin Tm layers on a Pt(1 1 1) substrate. The sample was annealed in order to form ordered surface alloys. Several TmPt intermetallic compounds are known to exist [1] ,[2] . Previous experiments have shown that solid state reactions occur when RE metals are deposited on a variety of metallic substrates even at ambient temperatures [3] ,[4] ,[5] . Due to the occurrence of homogeneous mixed valence in compounds [2] based on the RE earths Ce, Sm, Eu, Tm and Yb, these elements may be of particular interest. In this study predominantly trivalent Tm is observed.
In a previous work, the formation of an ordered LaPt(1 1 1) surface alloy was observed when a La on Pt overlayer system was annealed to 900 K. An analysis of thermal desorption spectra of CO from Pt and LaPt showed that the desorption energy was considerably lower in the case of the surface alloy, accompanied by an apparent shift of the centre of gravity of the d-band towards the Fermi-level [6] . The relative inertness to contamination in the vacuum chamber of the related CePt(1 1 1) system was also previously noted [7] ,[8] . On the other hand, in the LaRh(1 0 0) system recently studied, the CO desorption temperatures (and hence the desorption energies) were observed to increase [9] ,[10] , while the centre of gravity of the d-band made an apparent shift towards higher binding energies [9] . In this case, it was concluded that ordered alloys which consist of domains were formed, possibly introducing another complex mechanisms related to CO adsorption. One hypothesis, is that the 5σd band interaction is important in the CO adsorption on the rare earth Pt(1 1 1) systems. The presence of such strong resonant interactions of d band states in Pt and the 5σ orbital in CO [11] facilitates tuning of adsorption properties by changing the electronic structure of the catalytic active surface by alloy formation.
This work presents aspects of formation of TmPt(1 1 1) surface alloys including some structural and electronic properties, as well as CO adsorption studies.
2. Experimental
The photoemission measurements were performed in the home laboratory using a hemispherical SES 2002 electron energy analyser (Gammadata Scienta). For X-ray photoelectron spectroscopy (XPS) a monochromatized Al Kα X-ray source (Gammadata Scienta) was used to get the exciting radiation. For ultraviolet photoelectron spectroscopy (UPS) a He discharge lamp with a toroidal mirror monochromator (SPECS) was used. In the present experiment the total energy resolution for XPS and UPS was estimated to be about 0.4 and 0.1 eV, respectively, as determined from the width of the Fermi edge. Binding energies were calibrated by measuring the position of the Fermi edge. All spectra were measured in angle integrated mode around normal emission.
The temperature programmed desorption (TPD) spectra were recorded using a Transpector mass-spectrometer (Leybold-Inficon). The heating rate was 2 K/s, controlled by using a Eurotherm controller. The vacuum chamber was pumped by a 500 l/s turbo-molecular pump and a 240 l/s ion pump. It was assumed that the pumping rate of the vacuum chamber was so large that the signal from the mass spectrometer could be assumed to be proportional to the desorption rate.
The Pt(1 1 1) crystal was resistively heated and cooled by liquid nitrogen down to about 190 C. The temperature was measured by a thermocouple that was spot-welded to the rear of the sample. The Pt(1 1 1) crystal surface was cleaned by repeated cycles of Ar+ sputtering (15 min room temperature and 15 min 700 C), oxygen annealing at 1 × 108 Torr at 640 C for 5 min, and flash annealing to 1000 C in UHV. The cleanliness of the surface was verified by XPS. The ordering of the surface was studied by low energy electron diffraction (LEED). Tm was deposited from an evaporation source that consisted of a thermally heated tungsten basket that was thoroughly out-gassed before use. The deposition was performed with the Pt substrate at room temperature, and in certain cases with the substrate at liquid nitrogen temperature, where indicated. The effective thickness of the as-deposited Tm layer was estimated from the attenuation of the intensity of the Pt 4f core levels. The electron mean free path was in this work estimated to λ = 20 Å. We estimate the coverage in monolayers (ML) by assuming in the as-deposited case closed packed Tm on Pt with layer thickness estimated to be 3.5 Å, i.e. using the metallic radius of Tm. The photoemission intensity for all spectra was normalised to the background, and the formation of the different stages of the alloy was studied at different temperatures up to 900 C.
3. Results and discussion
3.1. LEED
Relatively diffuse LEED patterns were observed for Tm on Pt(1 1 1). Upon annealing slowly to 600 C of a sample having an effective Tm coverage of one to two monolayers, a diffuse (2 × 2) LEED pattern started forming around 550 C. The LEED spots appeared at the sharpest around 600700 C, Fig. 1 a. This pattern was stable to approximately 750 C. The photoemission results (see below), indicated a Pt enriched surface. As the sample was heated to 800 C, a more diffuse pattern consisting of multiple spots around the (1 × 1) reflexes appeared, Fig. 1 b. This structure will be denoted (1 × 1)+ in this paper. The latter LEED pattern did not form until the sample was heated to 900 C when more than about two monolayers (ML) Tm were deposited. The photoemission results (see below), indicated a considerable loss of the Tm 4d intensity, and the (1 × 1)+ LEED pattern was assigned to a submonolayer (thin) alloy, forming upon annealing to 900 C.
