It is difficult to interpret the structure of the thin surface alloy. The (1 × 1)+ pattern consists of a multiple spot structure around the (1 × 1) reflexes. The images are rather diffuse but may be interpreted to correspond to an (8 × 8) superstructure that may correspond to a domain structure [12] . When heating the sample to 800 C the photoemission intensities indicated less Tm in the surface alloy, caused either by evaporation of Tm from the top layer or solution into the bulk.
3.2. Photoemission
The attenuation of the intensity of the Pt 4f core levels was used to estimate the amount of deposited Tm. The core level intensities Tm 4d, Tm 5p, Pt 4f and the intensity of the two strongest Tm 4f multiplets were monitored during the annealing of the sample and used as indicators for alloying. The Pt 4f core levels showed small shifts from the clean sample of about 0.2 eV to lower binding energy after deposition of Tm, but no substantial shifts where observed after annealing. The Tm 4d, 5p and 4f levels all showed large shifts to lower binding energies of about 1.1, 0.8 and 0.8 eV; respectively, upon annealing to 600 C. In addition, UPS using He-I and He-II radiation was used to monitor the valence band. Finally, the work function was recorded during alloy formation. In the following section we will describe in more detail some of the experimental observations.
3.2.1. Core level intensities
Fig. 2 gives the variation in the core level intensities of Pt 4f and Tm 4d as a function of annealing temperature. The layer was estimated to have an effective thickness of 2.3 ML. It is observed that the Pt 4f intensity (shown by hollow squares, right axis in Fig. 2 ) increases up to 500 C. From 600 to 700 C, the Pt 4f intensity appears to increase more slowly. Upon heating to 800 and 900 C, the Pt 4f intensity increases more strongly. The Tm 4d intensity is nearly constant from room temperature (RT) up to 500 C. After further annealing the Tm 4d intensity drops nearly linearly with temperature. The observed LEED patterns in the different regions are indicated in the figure.
