The gradual changes in core level intensities, Fig. 2 , upon heating to 600 C, are interpreted as an indication of interdiffusion of Tm and Pt atoms. The (2 × 2) alloy formation at 500 C, may be due to the energy barrier required for restructuring the surface. As the temperature is raised towards 800900 C the upper layers of Tm atoms appear to either evaporate or dissolve, thereby leaving less than a monolayer of Tm at the surface, and the modified (1 × 1)+ LEED pattern appears.
3.2.2. XPSvalence band
The 4f levels of rare earths have been extensively studied in the literature [13] ,[14] ,[15] ,[16] ,[17] ,[18] .
Fig. 3 shows the valence band spectra recorded at room temperature after deposition of a Tm layer of estimated effective thickness of 2.3 ML. The bottom curve in Fig. 3 shows as a reference the XPS (Al Kα) valence band spectrum of clean Pt(1 1 1). The next curve shows the as-deposited Tm/Pt(1 1 1) at liquid nitrogen temperature. The remaining graphs show the valence band spectra recorded after annealing the Tm/Pt(1 1 1) system to 300, 600, 800, 850 and 900 C, from bottom to top, respectively. It is noted from Fig. 3 that only trivalent valence states [16] ,[17] are observed. The divalent Tm emission would be located in the binding energy region 02 eV in the valence band [17] and about 5 eV to lower binding energies relative to the trivalent emission for the 4d core levels [19] . It is noted, that thick divalent Tm layers has been reported for deposition at 13 K, which transformed into a trivalent layer upon heating to room temperatures [17] .
