Similar to the shifts observed for core level positions of Tm 4d and the 4f multiplet, we observed a distinct shift in the Tm 5p core level position by 0.8 eV towards lower binding energy when heating to 600 C. Subsequently, by heating the sample to 900 C, the peak shifts back by about 0.9 eV to higher binding energy relative to the peak position at 600 C. The observed core level shifts to lower binding energies upon annealing the Tm/Pt(1 1 1) to 600 C, are thus fingerprints of the formation of the (2 × 2) LEED thick alloy. Furthermore, the backward shifts upon annealing to 800900 C, are fingerprints of the (1 × 1)+ LEED thin alloy.
It is noted that the large core level shifts observed for the trivalent TmPt thick alloy are very interesting in the view of the final state chemical shift model [15] . In terms of the general trend described in Fig. 6 of Ref.
[15] for a selection of rare earth compounds, such large bulk shifts have only previously been reported for the mixed valence or the divalent state. We speculate that the contraction of the molar volume in the tetravalent photoemission final state is the reason for the large observed core level shifts for trivalent Tm in the TmPt alloy. The +0.9 eV relative shift to higher energies upon heating to (1 × 1)+, i.e. 800900 C, indicates, as a consequence, reduced coordination of Tm atoms in the thin TmPt alloy.
3.2.4. UPS valence band region
Due to photo-ionization cross section variations the UPS of the valence band region are mainly sensitive to the d electrons when using He-I radiation, and hence the Tm 4f multiplets are not readily observed [21] .
Fig. 6 shows the UPS spectra (angle integrated around normal emission) recorded from a 1.2 ML as-deposited Tm layer on Pt(1 1 1). The bottom figure shows the He-I spectrum recorded from clean Pt(1 1 1). The next spectrum is from the as-deposited Tm/Pt(1 1 1) sample at RT. The remaining spectra from the bottom to the top, show the HeI photoemission from the sample after annealing to 500, 600, 700 and 800 C. The LEED pattern, temperature and corresponding change in work function are indicated in Fig. 6 . We note that the work function for a 20 Å thick Tm layer was measured to be 3.3 eV.
