It is observed from Fig. 6 , that the valence band DOS of the as-deposited layer at RT appears to be shifted towards higher binding energies compared to clean Pt(1 1 1). Upon heating the sample, the intensity of the state denoted [A] increases towards a maximum at 600 C, with a slight shift towards lower binding energies. When the sample is heated to 800 C, the state [A] appears to transform into a new set of states which we denote [B] in the figure. However, at 700800 C the original state [C] of clean Pt(1 1 1) reappears, which may indicate enrichment of Pt at the surface. We note that at 800 C, the states at [B] which arise from the alloy surface are shifted towards the Fermi-level. It is also noted that the work function for the as-deposited sample is reduced by almost 2 eV, and subsequently increases as the temperature is increased. In fact, at 700900 C the work function of the system is higher than the one measured for the pure Pt(1 1 1) sample.
The PtTm phase diagram shows that several different bulk compounds exist [2] . The relatively diffuse LEED patterns may be related to the large number of possible compounds that may form. It is unclear which compounds are most likely to form at the surface, but we note from the phase diagram that only TmPt and TmPt3 seem to have vertical composition lines that extent all the way to the liquidsolid interface. The relatively high values of the work function, Fig. 6 , for both the (2 × 2) and (1 × 1)+ alloys suggest that the outermost atomic layer is Pt-rich.
3.3. CO adsorption
The adsorption/desorption properties of the surface alloy with respect to CO were monitored by temperature programmed desorption (TPD), and also by recording the C 1s core level intensity as function of temperature. The TPD experiments were performed subsequent to a CO dose of 6 L (1 L = 1 × 106 Torr s) at liquid nitrogen temperatures.
Fig. 7 shows the observed thermal desorption spectra in the temperature range 150850 K for the clean Pt(1 1 1) substrate, the (2 × 2) alloy which was formed by annealing to 600 C, and the (1 × 1)+ alloy which was formed by annealing in the temperature range 800900 C. The TPD spectrum for CO on clean Pt(1 1 1) shows a broad feature located between 300 and 550 K, centered at approximately 400 K. The TPD spectrum for the (2 × 2) TmPt alloy is much broader, ranging from 200 to 550 K, and centered at approximately 400 K. We observed three distinct peaks at approximately 327, 390 and 470 K. These peaks have been denoted Z3, Z2 and Z1, respectively, in Fig. 7 . In the TPD scan from CO on the (1 × 1)+ alloy, the main peak is located at 320 K with an additional shoulder at the low temperature side near 280 K. The centre of the TPD spectrum for CO on (1 × 1)+ is located near 310 K, which is about 90 K below the centre of the TPD trace from CO on clean Pt(1 1 1). Related observations were previously made for the La/Pt(1 1 1) and Ce/Pt(1 1 1) systems [6] ,[7] ,[8] . The core level intensities of the C 1s emission were consistent with the behaviour as described above. In addition, the measured binding energy of the C 1s core level was indicative of molecular CO, which was also confirmed by UPS (He-II) from the valence band region.
