Multiple peak structures in TPD may be caused by sites of different desorption energies, but may also be caused by lateral interactions among the adsorbed species on a surface. In fact, recent Monte-Carlo simulations [22] have demonstrated that adsorbateadsorbate interactions may result in distinct peak structures in the desorption spectra, such as e.g. the Z1Z3 in Fig. 7 . On the other hand, the comparison between the valence band spectra in Fig. 6 , and the TPD spectra in Fig. 7 , leads to interesting observations in conjunction with the model of Hammer et al.
[23] . For the thick (2 × 2) alloy, there is only a small shift of the centre of gravity of the d-band towards higher binding energies. As proposed in previous reports on the La/Pt(1 1 1) alloy [6] , in order to apply the concepts from the model of Hammer et al.
[23] , one must presume that the CO adsorption is rather dominated by the 5σd band interaction [11] , whereas the dominating coupling is normally the 2π*d band interaction [23] . In this view, the main coupling must be from the tail of the d-band [11] . In the case of the thin (1 × 1)+ alloy, the centre of gravity of the d-band moves towards the Fermi-level, due to the additional spectral weight at [B], see top spectrum in Fig. 6 , while the state [C] is unmodified compared to clean Pt(1 1 1). It is proposed that the 5σd band interaction moves out of resonance, and may thus be responsible for the 90 K downshift (with reference to to clean Pt(1 1 1)) of the centre of the TPD spectra resulting from CO on the (1 × 1)+ alloy. In order for such issues to be resolved through calculations, more structural information from e.g. the La/Pt(1 1 1), Ce/Pt(1 1 1) and Tm/Pt(1 1 1) alloys are required, including information related to strain [24] .
4. Summary
In this study we have applied XPS, UPS, LEED and TPD to investigate the formation of and CO adsorption/desorption properties of a Tm/Pt(1 1 1) surface alloy. For Tm overlayer thicknesses of more than about one ML, ordered alloys exhibiting (2 × 2) LEED patterns were observed to form at 600 C. The formation of the alloy is accompanied by shifts in the range 0.81.1 eV to lower binding energies of the Tm 4d, 5p and 4f12 core levels and multiplet lines. These shifts are taken as an indication of changed coordination due to the formation of TmPt alloys. Another LEED pattern forms as the alloy is further heated to 800900 C. This LEED pattern is a modified and relatively diffuse (1 × 1) pattern were the (1 × 1) reflexes consist of multiple spots. The formation of the latter alloy is accompanied by a 0.9 eV shift (relative to the 2 × 2 alloy) towards higher binding energies of the Tm 4d, 5p and 4f12 core levels and multiplet lines. The photoemission and work function results indicate that the surface of the alloys is Pt enriched.
The CO desorption from the alloy exhibiting the (2 × 2) LEED pattern occurs in the same temperature range as for CO on clean Pt(1 1 1). However, the desorption temperature for CO on the alloy exhibiting the modified (1 × 1) LEED pattern, was lowered by 80100 K compared to CO on clean Pt(1 1 1). This result is similar to previous observations of thermal desorption of CO from the La/Pt(1 1 1) system.


